result.execSummary:
The defendant Sara L. Doucette was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician. No contact with C. Meyer directly or indirectly. No phone calls, e-mails, text messages, written communications or by third party.
DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.
Defendant to undergo an alcohol and other drug assessment and comply with any further counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

Case Called @ 1:20 PM: Defendant Sara L. Doucette in court, appearing via video, pro se.   Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court to address Def's request for a furlough filed by Defendant.  Statement by Defendant as to her concerns relating to her son.  She requests a 2 week furlough to address matters relating to her children.  Court states what record is lacking for consideration of her release.  Per ADA:  Believes that Def is about half way thru serving her sentence and agrees more information should be provided.  The Court:  Presently the Court does not have information to decide this issue and once the Court is introduced with details as to what the needs required and any extension of treatment this issue can be reconsidered.  The Court has no basis today to authorize any furlough at this time. Court will reconsider upon further information indicating what has taken place and what it is will take place in the future as to her son's needs.  Will hold in abeyance this issue, absent further information.   Def states she cannot obtain further information without release.  Def instructed to perhaps contact DHS to obtain information requested by the Court.
